{{Infobox language | name = Nambya | nativename = Nanzva | pronunciation = | states = [[Zimbabwe]], [[Botswana]] | region = | ethnicity = [[Nambya|Nambya people]] | speakers = 80,000-100,000 | date = | ref = e18 | familycolor = Niger-Congo | fam2 = [[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] | fam3 = [[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] | fam4 = [[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern]] | fam5 = [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] | fam6 = '''Kalanga''' (S.10) | nation = [[Zimbabwe]] (both Kalanga and Nambya) | lc1 = nmq | ld1 = Nambya | glotto = namb1291 | glottorefname = Nambya }} The '''Nambya language''', or ''Nanzwa/Nanzva'', is a [[Bantu language]] spoken by the [[Nambya|Nambya people]]. It is spoken in northwestern [[Zimbabwe]], particularly in the town of [[Hwange]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Xe59ZMZjEQYC&pg=PA55&dq=nambya+hwange&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDuqa086vTAhXlL8AKHUfwDJ0Q6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=nambya%20hwange&f=false|title=The Politics of Language and Nation Building in Zimbabwe|last=Ndhlovu|first=Finex|date=2009-01-01|publisher=Peter Lang|year=|isbn=9783039119424|location=|pages=54|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t6TsCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA220&dq=nambya+hwange&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDuqa086vTAhXlL8AKHUfwDJ0Q6AEIRzAI#v=onepage&q=nambya%20hwange&f=false|title=Language Planning in Africa: The Cameroon, Sudan and Zimbabwe|last=Kamwangamalu|first=Nkonko|last2=Jr|first2=Richard B. Baldauf|last3=Kaplan|first3=Robert B.|date=2016-04-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781134916887|location=|pages=220|language=en}}</ref> with a few speakers in northeastern [[Botswana]]. It is either classified as a dialect of the [[Kalanga language]] or as a closely related language.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.jpanafrican.org/docs/vol3no6/3.5SomeSegmental.pdf|title = Some Segmental Phonological Processes Involving Vowels in Nambya: A Preliminary Descriptive Account|last = Kadenge|first = Maxwell, D.Phil|date = March 2010|website =|archive-url =|archive-date =|dead-url =|access-date =}}</ref> The Zimbabwean constitution, in particular the Education Act, as amended in 1990, recognises Nambya and Kalanga as separate indigenous languages.<ref name=":0" />
== Phonology == Nambya is a [[Tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language. It has a simple 5 vowel system and a typical Bantu consonant-vowel (CV) [[syllable]] structure. The language has onsetless syllables, but these are restricted to the word-initial position, making Nambya typical of the [[Southern Bantu languages]].<ref name=":0" />
=== Vowels === {| class="wikitable" ! ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Central vowel|Central]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Close vowel|Close]] |{{IPA link|i}} | |{{IPA link|u}} |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Mid vowel|Mid]] |{{IPA link|e}} | |{{IPA link|o}} |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | |{{IPA link|a}} | |}
== Morphology == Like many Bantu languages, Nambya has a highly [[Agglutination|agglutinative]] morphology.<ref name=":0" />
